I'm assuming your desire drops off after an hour for two reasons: your fingers start to hurt and you're tired of playing/practicing the same things over and over
After you've been playing for a while both of these problems will be solved, mostly haha
Your fingers won't hurt as much because you will have built up callouses and you will have more finger strength (also helps out if you've got a lady friend of you catch my drift) and you will realize that you don't need to press down on the strings near as hard to fret a note(the sooner you figure that one out the better). You won't be bored of playing the same things because you will have learned much more and you can start to write your own music, or interpret your favorite music in your own way(I love doing this because it helps you not only to understand song structure and the songwriting process in general, but it also helps you find your own style). Until then, listen to as many different genres of music as you can, fill your head with subliminal music ideas for later when you are writing or doodling(remember that learning to play any form of music is just as much about LISTENING as it is about playing). Hope I helped!

Say anything has a lot of great stuff that translates well on an acoustic, and a good amount of acoustic songs as well! All of their songs are fairly easy to sing along with and have great meaningful lyrics. His playing style uses a lot of inversions that use 2-3 finger groupings. I would suggest "Alive With the Glory of Love", "Total Revenge", and "I Want to Know Your Plans".
Some that I'm not sure wether or not they use primarily 3 fingers, but are still great songs, are "Death for My Birthday", "Eloise", "The Futile", "Do Better", "Yellow Cat/Red Cat", and "Hate Everyone".
The most difficult part of his playing style is his right hand rhythm technique so maybe with your fretting hand injured it could be a great opportunity to put some work in on your right hand.
He also has a few simple but satisfying solos in their songs as well. Hope I helped!
